npassenger limousine stands out In full\nview. A feature of this exhibit Is one\nof the Vulcan electric gear shifting de\nvices, mounted and In full operation.\nDisplays Flic Electrics.\nThe Emerson1 Ormo display consists\nof five Detroit electric broughams of\nthe latest type and construction. The re\nmainder of their exhibit consists of\nthree 1511 Apperson cars, including one\nroadster. The exhibit of the Mitchell\nLewis Motor Company's line is novel.\nThe display of the Hudson Automobile\nCompany comprises big and little Hud\nson \"six\" touring cars, a cabriolet and\na sedan. The Argo electric broughams\nalso form part or the same exhibit. The\nRegal exhibit, consisting of touring cars,\na roadster, and a chassis, attracted a\nnumber of visitors. Another popular ex\nhibit Is that of T. Lamar Jackson, who\nhandles the Stevens-Duryea line. The\ntwo cars on display Include a five-passenger\ncar equipped with \"wire wheels and\na seven-passenger touring car, both\nfinished In mulberry- red.\nTwo Ohio electric broughams are being\ndisplayed In the space adjoining the\nEtevens-Duryea. The new six-cylinder\nMarmon \"41\" made Its bow to the public\nIt Is finished In black and red running\ngear. In addition to this, car there are\nalso shown the highest priced car In the\nfihow a SowOOO sir \"44 Marmon of the\nseven-passenger type. The latest model\nWoods electric brougham also forms part\nf tho display of this concern.\nExhibits of Accessories.\nOn the west side of the hall Is located\nthe velvet shock absorber and rear signal\nlamp display of Chesley Harveycutter.\nNext in line Is to be found an unusually\nlarge display of automobile accessories\nby the National Electrical Supply Com\npany. The Krit-Washlngton Motor Com\npany occupies the next space, two tour\ning models of the latest type, one equip\nped with wire wheels, forming the dis\nplay. MtHer-Dudley Company has an exhibit\nwhich consists of Gray and Davis light\ning systems, Bosch magnetos and spark\nplugs and Hess-Bright bearings.\nIrvin T. Docohoe has a large display\nat automobile accessories. He is fea\nturing the J. M. shock absorber. Ieroy\nMark has space and Is telling of the\nwhys and wherefores of automobile fire\nInsurance. The Edison Electric Storage\nBattery and Equipment Company has an\nelectrical display.\nThe Indiana truck exhibit of R. E.\nLankford consists of one. two and three\nton chassis and. bodies, being shown for\nme first time here The Wllcox-Trux dls-\nIplay of the Coagreialoaal, garage ioccu-\nI -.1.. Mia mmtlrm nuts' Md Of .IBS BaH.\nTha Warrington Motor Car Company\nhas two of tha latest i-awier-mHger- mw\neta.\nAnother busy exhibit last night waa\nthat- of the W-1 n!th Company, which\nconcern recently closed the agency -tor\nthe DetroKer .car. Two -models, of tha\n1H1 type are sfcown.\nTho David Motor Car Company Is\nshowing a Davia six-cylinder car, finished\nin maroon.\nA H. Gregory hag a full line of marine\nmotors.\nnrh- A Rasa la ditrfavlnr a full line\nof automobile accessories. Tha A. V.\nshock absorber la attracting much at\ntention, as are also tha tabloid and solold,\nfirst-aid outfits. The O. 8. shock ab\nsorber la being shown by the Waldron\nrenresentatlvea, The Briscoe small car\narrived last evening. Other exhibitors In\nclude the Capital Havings nan, the\nTolman Laundry and the Express Spark\nPlug Company.\nMrs. Bofcn la Jssprovlsg.\nThe condition of Mrs. Belle Bonn, who\nwas seriously hurt Saturday afternoon\nnear her home In Warrenton, Va., when\nshe waa violently thrown from a buggy\nby a runaway horse, showed consider\nable improvement yesterday at Provi\ndence Hospital. Mrs. Bohn waa brought\nto Washington Saturday night suffering\nfrom a compound fracture of tne skuil\nShe waa operated on by Dr. James F.\nMitchell. .Mrs. Bohn was bom In Wash\nington and is prominent In the social life\nof the Capital and Virginia.\nREDHELD IS HOPEFUL\nOF BUSINESS OUTLOOK\nSays Mr. Wilson's Message Placet\nPresident in Line with Best\nCommercial Thought\n.s.\nSEES PERMANENT PROSPERITY\nSecretary Redfleld, of the Department\nof Commerce, took a hopeful view of the\nbusiness outlook, and In an Interview\ngiven to The Washington Herald de\nclared that the President's message\nproved that the President Is In line with\nthe best business thought of the coun\ntry and has outlined a policy which will\nImprove business conditions, restore pop\nular confidence In business, and lead to\na permanent prosperity.\nThe Secretary reviewed crop conditions\nand other fundamental conditions\nthroughout the country, declaring that\nall signs pointed to prosperous times. One\nof the strongest Indications of business\nexpansion, he said, was the movement\namong American manufacturers looking\nto the enlargement of their export trade\nSecretary Redfleld said:\n\"I am sure that the spirit of the Presi\ndent's message read to Congress today\nwill strike a responsive chord In busi\nness circles all over the land. Already\nsuch depression as had existed here and\nthere has begun to pass away. The\nmovement seems to be upward and for\nward generally. It is not a rush or a\nboom, and It Is well that it is not. be\ncause rushes and booms are apt to last\nbut a little while\"\n\"The fundamental economic conditions\nof the country are sound: there la no exces\nsite speculation, debts are well liqui\ndated, the fanner of the South and West\nhas received adequate return from his\ncrops, our manufacturers are holding\ntheir place In the foreign markets at a\ntime when low prices prevail In Eng\nland and Germany, and have tested our\ncompeting power to the utmost. The cur\nrency bill has removed .the threatened\ndanger from an. Inflexible' financial con\ndition; the tariff, even by those who\noppose It, is admitted at the worst to be\nmuch better than they feared, and at the\nbest, to be helpfuL What is there to\nfear?\"\n7T\nr\nimWL WCffliE\nSEEN IN ALASKA BH1\nMet-M&eriWMts Rwfewd Would Be\nStap m OrtsjboBof\nr Sockfisau\nJUDGESHIP QUESTION IS UP.\nWilson and MeReyaoIds Alas Dis\ncuss District Federal Places.\nPresident Wilson and Attorney General\nMcReynolds yesterday conferred concern\ning appointments of four Judges of the\nMunicipal Court and other Federal posi\ntions In the District, but If they reached\na decision on any of the Jobs they did not\nmake the fact known.\nAttorney General McReynolds, who is\nknown to be opposed to nominations to\nthe bench of men above fifty years, has\nreceived hundreds of letters. It Is stated,\ndeclaring that Judge Charles S. Bundy.\nw ho seeks reappointment, has not allowed\nage to interfere with his work.\nSenator Vardaman. who has planned to\noppose the reappointment of Judge Robert\nH. Terrell, colored, has not yet been In\nconference with the President. It is un\nderstood the President will ask Varda\nman to cease objecting to every colored\nman nominated for a Federal Job.\nKENTON URGES CIVIL SERVICE\nGovernment ownership and control of\nrailroads was discussed In tha Senate\nyesterday afternoon In connection with\ntha Alaska railroad bin. senator mc-\nCuraber Insisted that government owner\nship was the first step In the direction\nof a soclallstlo movement and that It\nwould and In building up a great politi\ncal machine made up of railway em\nployes, whose salaries would be much\nhigher than are paid under present con\nditions.\nSenator Kenvon. replying to Mr. mc-\nCumbers charge that railway ownership\nand operation by the government would\nresult in a great political machine, in\nsisted that it could be guarded against\nby applying the merit system and the\ncivil service protection to the employes.\nSenator Smith, of Michigan, took ex\nceptlpn to the suggestion that the civil\nservice system was carnea out in gooa\nfaith and that political appointments are\nmade on merit. He characterised Sena\ntor Kenvon's Idea that railway employee\nunder government ownership would bo\nkept out of politics by the civil service\nas \"another Uloplan dream.\"\nReferring to the eatlmale by Mr. Thome,\nof the Iowa commission, that govern\nment ownership would save 1150,000,000 a\nyear, Mr. Kenyon observed:\n'If the efficiency of our transportation\nwas not diminished and If civil service\nwas kept strictly intact so that tha em\nployes would not be thrust Into politics,\nthe people may well Inquire whether such\nan amount should not be saved, because\nIn the end. It comes out of them.\nIn the course of the discussion or the\nbill Senator Chamberlain, who is In\ncharge of the bill, assured Senators that\nIt waa the Intention of the committee\nto limit the amount of the total expend!\nure on account of railroads In Alaska\nto S35.000.0e0i the total mileage to 1.000 and\nthat possibly, there might be a limitation\nas to whatllhe average cost per mile\nshould be, (Senator William Alden Smith\nwaa of' the opinion that the road ought\nto be built for 140,000 a mile on the aver\nage.\nSecretary of the Interior Lane yester\nday forwarded to Representative Hous\nton, chairman of the House Committee\non Territories, a lengthy letter giving\na recent history of railroad construction\nIn lands newly opened, which he believes\nwill be of help to members of Congress\nwho are now considering the bill which\nprovides that the government build a\nrailroad to be operated In the newly\nopened lands of Alaska. The following\nIs an extract from the Introduction of\nSecretary Lane's letter:\n\"If we are to open Alaska we must\ndo so either by subsidizing railroads with\nland and money grants or by government\nconstruction, as no other method has\nbeen devised in this or any other country.\"\nBSBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBSBBBBBBBBBBBBBNSBBsaSHBSBBBBBaBBBBaBBSa\nSE'SH-lOGENAnUN ILLS\n\"WOW eggs are probably produced y\nsjerags-jisea eeia. ma ,os,sbj to\nX.m.m moat be deposited by the largest\nOne \"of \"the most surprising' facts In the\neeia life Is that all Individuals of both\n\"rr\" alter spawning once. Tha wto\ncipai damage dona by the eel Is to\nthe spawn of food fishes. This Is con\naumed In great quantities especially at\nRACE SUICIDE UNKNOWN\nAMONG PROLIFIC EELS\nFrom 5.000.000 to 20.000.000 Eggs\nPer Fish Not at All\nUnusual.\nUnited States Commissioner of Fish\nand Fisheries Hugh M. Smith, in an ar\nticle written for the National Geographic\nSociety, dispels much mystery that has\nhitherto surrounded the life of the com\nmon eel. \"When the complete life of the\neel is cleared up, it will doubtless be\nshown to have a more remarkable his\ntory than any other fish possesses,\" he\nsays.\n\"While the remarkable habits of the eel\nremained unknown or defied the elucida\ntion, of the early observers. Imagination\nran riot, fiction and fable were accepted\nas fact, and the eel was loaded with an\nIncubus of Impossible attributes. The\nmost extraordinary theories and beliefs\nhave been entertained regarding the\nspawning habits of the eel. from the\ntime of Aristotle to the present day. The\ncau;e of all the speculations and mis\nconceptions has been the fact that eels\ndo not spawn within the confines of the\ncontlnen's or where human observation\nis possible.\n\"The habits of the eel at the time of\nspawning are entirely unknown The\neggs are never deposited in water less\nthan 1.000 meters deep. They hatch at or\nnear the surface, where they aro car\nried by their natural buoyancy. From\ncounts and estimates based on Immature\nMBST ICARTLAID AMIM.\nGallandet Qalat Clashes wlta An\ncleat Rivals Today.\nGallaudet'a basket-ball team will play\nMaryland Agricultural College in tha\nKendall Green gymnasium this after\nnoon at 4 o'clock.\n,s!f Josing to tha strong University\n\"tiim qumt last Saturday. Qallau\npet as shown Improvement In shoot\ning and passing under the excellent\ncoaching of \"Mickey\" Xelblhtr and wiU\nthe game confident of victory.\nThat the rams will tv hntlv mniHM\nfrom start to finish Is most likely be\ncause of the keen rivalry of both In-\niiiuuong in athletics and It will be a\ngame worth seeing.\nThe probable Kne-up of Gallaudet wIU\nbe: Capf. Durian, right forward; Rock\nwell, left forward: Rasrauasen, center;\nKeeley. right jusrd; Classen, left guard.\nMERCHANTS PLANNING\nGET-TOGETHER DINNER\nFebruary 24 Selected as 'Date and\nRaleigh Hotel as the\nPlace.\nEXPECT NOTABLE GATHERING\nWorld's Foremost\nElectric\nAutomobile\nBuilt by the largest factory in the world building exclusively\nelectric vehicles, and not only the largest, but the strongest finan\ncially. There are no perplexing problems to solve in the purchase\nof an electric car.\nThe owners of Detroit electric cars have the satisfaction of\nknowing they have the best that can be produced.\nEMERSON ORME,\nDistributers\n1407 H St.. N. W. Telephone Main 7695\nThe third annual merchants' get-together\ndinner of the Retail Merchants'\nAssociation Is announced for Tuesday\nevening. February 24. at the Raleigh\nHotel.\nThis announcement was made last\nnight by M. A. Leese, chairman of the\ndinner committee, and arrangements are\nalready Hfoot to make tho dinner the\nmost ambitious and successful function\nthat has ever been attempted by the\nbusiness men of Washington.\nThe committee appointed by President\nR. P. Andrews to arrange for the dinner\nIs getting under way In great shape, and\nat a meeting of the executive committee\nheld Monday at noon some of the big\nwork that has been planned for the din\nner was apportioned.\nThe committeemen stated thelr.determl\nnatlon to make special efforts to bring\ntogether a notable number of the retail\nmerchants of Washington about the\n\"get-together\" board.\nThe following is the personnel of the\ncommittee In charge of the dinner: M. A.\nIse. chairman; E. C. Graham, treas\nurer; Charles J. Columbus, secretary: R.\nP. Andrews. Isaac Cans. J. Henry Small.\nJulius Garflnklc. Joseph Strasburger. Sid\nney West. Simon Kann, Harry King. F.\nW. MacKenzie, Claude K. Miller. Z. D.\nBiacklstone, W. W. Griffith. Gerson Nord-\nlinger. Samuel Ia. Willett. Edward W.\nZea. A. D. Prince. Morris Hahn. J. M.\nBird, James F. Oyster. J. M. BurrelU T.\nC Dulln, A. Llsner. R. X. Martin. Iu!s\nBoeckstyn. Charles S. McGuIggan. Louis\nLevy. E. H. Snider, William John Eynon,\nGeorge E. Hebbard, and O. J. De MolL\n5 ill 1\n.',ri-\nr\nOF HUMNG IK\nWilliam Eberwein, Civil War VeWaa.\nDeclares He Thought It No Sta\ntcf End Misery. J\nHAD SUFFERED WITH CANCER\nPhiladelphia, Jan. -WUUam Eber\nweln. eighty years old. a -veteran of tha\ncivil war, was convicted todayv of the\nmurder of his wife, sUty-flvs yeara old,\nanil npnlnA in avn Year. BraCticel-\nly a Ufa sentence for hint. Hsralatedl\ni .k\",'tfir.Ct.vi!'.T;, \"vt-l\nrw. NwN fro: V\n-VA\nTdWCibl\n'4\nSatv Francisco, Jan. 20.-AIH Southern\nPaeMo trains wart delayed from on to\nhours today because rotary plows\nte clearing the mate, line through the\nMerra Nevadas have buried th aiding\nbetween ten and fifteen-feet deep with\nsnow.\nNew Tork. Jan. -A wireless re\nceived here this afternoon stated that the\nsteamship Oscar H, of the Scandinavian\nAmerican line, bad suffered a breakdown\nwhile en route from Copenhagen to this\nport, and was proceeding slowly with\n245 passengers under power fumlihed by\nio vun engine.\nBoston, Jan. Ja-Hope for the Boston\nhow he had put his wife out of th way four-masted schooner Prescott Talmer,\n7. t ora. was prac\ntically abandoned today when the United\nStates revenue-cutters Androscoggin and\nOresham wired to this port: \"No news\nof the Prescott Pelmer.\"\nafter she had pleaded and begged him\nto end her sufferings.\n\"My wife suffered for seven years with\nvertigo,\" ho said. \"Three yeara ago ah\ngot a cancer on her foot She suffered\nawfully. She was always falling down.\nShe went to a hospital, but It did her\npi good. After sh csm horn, tha day\nthia thing happened. I was out in the\nyard. Sh said she was going up stairs\nto Isy down. A little whll later I cam\nIn for my pipe, and I saw her at the\nbottom of th stairs. She must have\nfsllen all the way down from th top.\n\"I 'knew she wu terribly hurt. She\nsaid. 'I'm suffering awfully. William, and\nI want to die. You do It, Winhun. End\nIt all for roe. It's no sin.' says she. \"when\nI'm suffering so.'\n\"I had a board In my hand that I had\nbrought In out of the yard. I looked at\nher lying ther hurt so and guessed, too.\nIt wouldn't be a sin. I tapped her on the\nhead with the board. She didn't moan\nmuch and once when I slopped she kind\nof whispered: Oo on. it won't be long.'\n\"So I kept on tapping her and sh got\nquiet and 'it seemed to ma contented\nwhile I tapped her with th board. Then\nI was arrested and taken to \"prison; where\nPre been dying ever since.\"\nEXPECT ABOUT 100 DELEGATES.\nXatlesal Lienor Lesgse Sleets 1\"\nConveatlam Here February 3-5.\nMore than 100 delegates are expected\nto attend the twenty-first annual conven\ntion or the National Liquor League, to be\nheld In this city February S-5 at the\nNational Hotel.\nThe convention flcst was set ror toaay.\ntomorrow, and Friday, but was post\nponed. William A. Engel. Samuel J.\nStelnberger. and Patrick F. Carr aro del\negates from the local Federation of Liquor\nDealers. Aurust Brahler is chairman of\nthe committee on entertainment and is\npreparing a good program for the vis\nitors.\nBIO CBOWD ATTENDS LECTDBE.\nXrrriurr to Vse Andltortaaa all\nEpiphany for Bishop Ttowe.\nIt was nceesary to use tho main audl-\ntorium of the Church of the Epiphany I\nlast night to accommodate the attendance I\nat the io nt meeting of tne isunaay scnooi\nInstitute and the Diocesan branch of the I\nWoman's Auxiliary of Epiphany parish I\nhall.\nA Personally Conducted Tour in\nAlaska\" was the tide of an address given\nby Bishop Peter Trimble Rowe, of\nAlaska. The lecture was comprenensi e\nIn detail, shotting tho wonderful growth\nend development of Alaska. A business\nmeeting of the Sunday school institute\nwas held shortly before the lecture In the\nparish halL\nSee the Most Modern\nAdvances in Motordom\nV.\nAUTO\nSHOW\nConvention Hall\n5th and L Ste. N. W.\nJanuary 19 to 24, 1914\nDaily 10 A. M. to 10:30 P. M.\nCONCERTS Afternoons and Evenings\nby the U. S. MARINE BAND\nLieut. Wm. H. Santclmann, Leader\nAdmission 25c SyD'y 50c\nSEE\nTHE SENSATION\nof tkt\nAUTOMOBILE SHOW\nHftniS\nELECTRIC GEARSHaFT\nTHE PROBEY-HAYNES MOTOR CAR COMPANY,\nSalwtwaw, 123 Whcmmi Avaa N. W.\nNew York. Jsn. M.-The worst tie, up\nIn the history of the New Tork subway\noccurred today when a broken axle\nwrecked a train at Nlnenty-slxth street.\nThe system was tied up for three hours\nand-'mor than were delayed.\nAlbany, N. T.. Jan. M.-Norma condl\ntlons are rapidly being restored today\non the Delaware and Hudson Railroad,\nwhich was tied up completely yesterday\nby the shortest and most effective strike\non record. All of tha 5,000 employes-who\nstruck aro back at work.\nQueenstown, Ireland. Jan. 50. The Cu\nnard liner Lusltanla arrived here today\nwith the master and crew of th Nova\nScotlan schooner Mayflower on board.\nThe Mayflower was wrecked in a storm\nIn mid-Atlantic and burned at sea after\nher crew had deserted her.\nMovements of Ocean Steamships.\nNew Tork, Jan. 20. Arrived: Russia,\nLlbau; Madonna, Lisbon: Bovlc, Liver\npool; Excelsior, .Rotterdam: Manhattan.\nAntwerp.\nSailed: Kronprizessln Cecllle. Bremen, 10\na. m.v.New Amsterdam, Rotterdam. 10\na. m.; Verona, Naples. 11 a. m.; Pan\nnonla, Naples. 13 m.; Cristobal. Colon, 3\np. m.\nlargest Horning Circulation.\nMMSTtrS WIE HYES\nSPOUSE TO m MATE'\nMrs. J.'H. Foster, of Atlanta, Sect\nPastor-Husband Go Back to\nPretty Widow.\nSAYS \"ITS BETTER TtirYT WAT\"\n'Atlanta, Go, Jan. 20. Rev. J. H. Pos\nter, a prominent Baptist minister of At\nlanta, has been turned over by bis wife\nfto young and pretty' Mrs. Maude Deane,\nwnom ma preacner cans nis soul mats\nMrs. Poster announced today that she\nwould not prosecute her husband and\nMrs Deane, who- were recently arrested\non a statutory charge. Poster and Mrs.\nDeane admitted their Illicit relatons.\n1 think It la better for all concerned\nto let Mrs. Deane hav my husband,' aaid\nMrs. Foster. \"I shall not prosecute.\"\n\"I am glad Mra. Foster has decided\nto act sensibly,\" said Foster. \"If ln\nhad reached that decision long eo this\ntrouble would have been avoded. I shall\nget a divo'cs and marry Mrs. Dean.\nI Intend to remain In the ministry. I\nhave done nothing save follow my hett.\"\n\"SAHTA CIAUS GIRL HAPPY.\"\nSenator Williams Tells Olive Wilson\nHe Indorses lfer Plan.\n\"Senator John Sharp Williams waa\nperfectly grand to me when I saw him\nyesterday morning about giving his\nsupport to the bill which I want In\ntroduced into Congress granting the\nfranking privilege of the mails to gifts\nsent to destitute children at Christmas.\nHe ssld that it was a very pretty Idea\nand that he thoroughly Indorsed It.\"\nThis waa the comment of Miss Olive\nMay Wilson, the \"Santa Claus girl.\" of\nPhiladelphia, who last Christmas sent\nover 5,000 toys to the poor children of\nthe country, when asked about her in\nInterview with Senator Wlllams, of\nMississippi, yesterday.\nThis morning she will see Secretary\nDaniels. Secretary Bryan. Speaker Clark.\nRepresentative Underwood. Secretary\nLane, and Admiral Dewey. She also ex\npects to see Vice President Marshall, who\nhas already voiced his approval of the\nplan.\nMARMON\n\"The Easiest Riding Car in the World'\nDon't Miss Seeing the Hit\nof the auto show the\nMARMON\nA six-cylinder car of\nample power, moderate\nsize and reasonable price.\nPOTOMAC MOTOR\nCAR CO.\n1226 Conn. Ave. N. W. Tel. N. 2000\nXlfteaS\nNOBBY\nTREAD\nItSa\nThese two famous tires are\nin use on more cars thru\nout the world than all other\nnon-skid tires put together.\nDistributers:\nNatioaaJ Electrical Supply Co.,\n1328-1330 New York are.,\nWaskiattoB, D. C.\nCHAIN\nTREAD\nMi\nTOONE M. 7M. NEW S AND T PA-\nacoger Touring vara, sx.oo per sour\nup. Eest service. LOt races. Any\ntime. Any place. PEOPLE'S AUTO\nUUUNO